[{"category":"section","location":"reference/#Reference","page":"Reference","text":"","title":"Reference"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#ITensorMPS.MPS-Tuple{Vector{<:ITensors.Index}, Any, Vector{<:ITensors.ITensor}}","page":"Reference","text":"MPS(sites::Vector{<:Index}, state, U::Vector{<:ITensor}; kwargs...)\n\nReturn an MPS with site indices sites by applying the circuit U to the starting state state.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ITensorMPS.MPS"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#ITensorGaussianMPS._eigen_gaussian_blocked-Tuple{Any}","page":"Reference","text":"Takes a single-particle Hamiltonian in blocked Dirac format and finds the fermionic transformation U that diagonalizes it\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS._eigen_gaussian_blocked"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#ITensorGaussianMPS.correlation_matrix_to_mps-Tuple{Vector{<:ITensors.Index}, ITensorGaussianMPS.AbstractSymmetry}","page":"Reference","text":"correlation_matrix_to_mps(s::Vector{<:Index}, Λ::AbstractMatrix{ElT};\n                          eigval_cutoff::Float64 = 1e-8,\n                          maxblocksize::Int = size(Λ, 1),\n                          kwargs...)\n\nReturn an approximation to the state represented by the correlation matrix as a matrix product state (MPS).\n\nThe correlation matrix should correspond to a pure state (have all eigenvalues of zero or one).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.correlation_matrix_to_mps"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#ITensorGaussianMPS.diag_corr_gaussian-Tuple{AbstractMatrix}","page":"Reference","text":"Takes a single-particle correlation matrix in interlaced Dirac format and finds the fermionic transformation U that diagonalizes it\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.diag_corr_gaussian"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#ITensorGaussianMPS.diag_corr_gaussian-Tuple{LinearAlgebra.Hermitian}","page":"Reference","text":"Takes a single-particle correlation matrix in interlaced Dirac format and finds the fermionic transformation U that diagonalizes it\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.diag_corr_gaussian"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#ITensorGaussianMPS.eigen_gaussian-Tuple{Any}","page":"Reference","text":"Takes a single-particle Hamiltonian in interlaced Dirac format and finds the complex fermionic transformation U that diagonalizes it.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.eigen_gaussian"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#ITensorGaussianMPS.frobenius_distance-Tuple{AbstractMatrix, AbstractMatrix}","page":"Reference","text":"frobenius_distance(M1::AbstractMatrix, M2::AbstractMatrix)\n\nComputes the Frobenius distance √tr((M1-M2)'*(M1-M2)).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.frobenius_distance"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#ITensorGaussianMPS.get_gaussian_GS_corr-Tuple{AbstractMatrix}","page":"Reference","text":"Takes a single-particle Hamiltonian in interlaced Dirac format and outputs the ground state correlation matrix (with the input Hamiltonians element type).\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.get_gaussian_GS_corr"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#ITensorGaussianMPS.givens_rotations-Tuple{ITensorGaussianMPS.ConservesNfParity}","page":"Reference","text":"givensrotations(v0::ConservesNfParity)\n\nFor a vector\n\nv=_v0.data\n\nfrom a fermionic Gaussian state, return the 4*length(v)-1 real Givens/Boguliobov rotations g and the norm r such that:\n\ng * v ≈ r * [n == 2 ? 1 : 0 for n in 1:length(v)]\n\nwith g being composed of diagonal rotation aligning pairs of complex numbers in the complex plane, and Givens/Boguliobov Rotations with real arguments only, acting on the interlaced single-particle space of annihilation and creation operator coefficients.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.givens_rotations"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#ITensorGaussianMPS.givens_rotations-Union{Tuple{AbstractVector{ElT}}, Tuple{ElT}} where ElT","page":"Reference","text":"givens_rotations(v::AbstractVector)\n\nFor a vector v, return the length(v)-1 Givens rotations g and the norm r such that:\n\ng * v ≈ r * [n == 1 ? 1 : 0 for n in 1:length(v)]\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.givens_rotations"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#ITensorGaussianMPS.make_real_if_possible-Tuple{AbstractMatrix, Vector}","page":"Reference","text":"Checks if we can make degenerate subspaces of a U0 real by multiplying columns or rows with a phase\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.make_real_if_possible"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#ITensorGaussianMPS.make_subspace_real_if_possible-Tuple{AbstractMatrix}","page":"Reference","text":"Checks if we can make a degenerate subspace of the eigenbasis of an operator real by multiplying columns or rows with a phase\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.make_subspace_real_if_possible"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#ITensorGaussianMPS.order_schur-Tuple{LinearAlgebra.Schur}","page":"Reference","text":"Schur decomposition of skew-hermitian matrix\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.order_schur"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#ITensorGaussianMPS.slater_determinant_to_mps-Tuple{Vector{<:ITensors.Index}, AbstractMatrix}","page":"Reference","text":"slater_determinant_to_mps(s::Vector{<:Index}, Φ::AbstractMatrix; kwargs...)\n\nGiven indices and matrix of orbitals representing a Slater determinant, compute a matrix product state (MPS) approximately having the same correlation matrices as this Slater determinant.\n\nOptional keyword arguments:\n\neigval_cutoff::Float64=1E-8 - cutoff used to adaptively determine the block size (eigenvalues must be closer to 1 or 0 by an amount smaller than this cutoff for their eigenvectors be labeled as \"inactive\" orbitals)\nmaxblocksize::Int - maximum block size used to compute inactive orbitals. Setting this to a smaller value can lead to faster running times and a smaller MPS bond dimension, though the accuracy may be lower.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.slater_determinant_to_mps"},{"category":"section","location":"#ITensorGaussianMPS.jl","page":"Home","text":"(Image: Stable) (Image: Dev) (Image: Build Status) (Image: Coverage) (Image: Code Style) (Image: Aqua)\n\nCitation Open-access preprint\n(Image: DOI) (Image: arXiv)\n\nA package for creating the matrix product state of a free fermion (Gaussian) state.","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.jl"},{"category":"section","location":"#Support","page":"Home","text":"<img class=\"display-light-only\" src=\"assets/CCQ.png\" width=\"20%\" alt=\"Flatiron Center for Computational Quantum Physics logo.\"/>\n<img class=\"display-dark-only\" src=\"assets/CCQ-dark.png\" width=\"20%\" alt=\"Flatiron Center for Computational Quantum Physics logo.\"/>\n\nITensorGaussianMPS.jl is supported by the Flatiron Institute, a division of the Simons Foundation.","title":"Support"},{"category":"section","location":"#Installation-instructions","page":"Home","text":"This package resides in the ITensor/ITensorRegistry local registry. In order to install, simply add that registry through your package manager. This step is only required once.\n\njulia> using Pkg: Pkg\n\njulia> Pkg.Registry.add(url = \"https://github.com/ITensor/ITensorRegistry\")\n\nor:\n\njulia> Pkg.Registry.add(url = \"git@github.com:ITensor/ITensorRegistry.git\")\n\nif you want to use SSH credentials, which can make it so you don't have to enter your Github ursername and password when registering packages.\n\nThen, the package can be added as usual through the package manager:\n\njulia> Pkg.add(\"ITensorGaussianMPS\")","title":"Installation instructions"},{"category":"section","location":"#Examples","page":"Home","text":"ITensorGaussianMPS.jl can help create starting states for DMRG. For example:\n\nusing ITensorGaussianMPS: slater_determinant_to_mps\nusing ITensorMPS: MPO, OpSum, dmrg, inner, random_mps, siteinds\nusing LinearAlgebra: Hermitian, diagm, eigen\n\n# Half filling\nN = 20\nNf = N ÷ 2\n\n@show N, Nf\n\n# Hopping\nt = 1.0\n\n# Free fermion hopping Hamiltonian\nh = Hermitian(diagm(1 => fill(-t, N - 1), -1 => fill(-t, N - 1)))\n_, u = eigen(h)\n\n# Get the Slater determinant\nΦ = u[:, 1:Nf]\n\n# Create an mps for the free fermion ground state\ns = siteinds(\"Fermion\", N; conserve_qns = true)\nψ0 = slater_determinant_to_mps(s, Φ; maxblocksize = 4)\n\n# Make an interacting Hamiltonian\nU = 1.0\n@show U\n\nos = OpSum()\nfor b in 1:(N - 1)\n    os .+= -t, \"Cdag\", b, \"C\", b + 1\n    os .+= -t, \"Cdag\", b + 1, \"C\", b\nend\nfor b in 1:N\n    os .+= U, \"Cdag * C\", b\nend\nH = MPO(os, s)\n\nprintln(\"\\nFree fermion starting energy\")\n@show inner(ψ0', H, ψ0)\n\n# Random starting state\nψr = random_mps(s, n -> n ≤ Nf ? \"1\" : \"0\")\n\nprintln(\"\\nRandom state starting energy\")\n@show inner(ψr', H, ψr)\n\nprintln(\"\\nRun dmrg with random starting state\")\ndmrg(H, ψr; nsweeps = 10, maxdim = [10, 20, 40, 60], cutoff = 1.0e-12)\n\nprintln(\"\\nRun dmrg with free fermion starting state\")\ndmrg(H, ψ0; nsweeps = 4, maxdim = 60, cutoff = 1.0e-12)\n\nThis will output something like:\n\n(N, Nf) = (20, 10)\nU = 1.0\n\nFree fermion starting energy\ninner(ψ0', H, ψ0) = -2.3812770621299357\n\nRandom state starting energy\ninner(ψr', H, ψr) = 10.0\n\nRun dmrg with random starting state\nAfter sweep 1 energy=6.261701784151 maxlinkdim=2 time=0.041\nAfter sweep 2 energy=2.844954346204 maxlinkdim=5 time=0.056\nAfter sweep 3 energy=0.245282430911 maxlinkdim=14 time=0.071\nAfter sweep 4 energy=-1.439072132586 maxlinkdim=32 time=0.098\nAfter sweep 5 energy=-2.220202191945 maxlinkdim=59 time=0.148\nAfter sweep 6 energy=-2.376787647893 maxlinkdim=60 time=0.186\nAfter sweep 7 energy=-2.381484153892 maxlinkdim=60 time=0.167\nAfter sweep 8 energy=-2.381489999291 maxlinkdim=57 time=0.233\nAfter sweep 9 energy=-2.381489999595 maxlinkdim=49 time=0.175\nAfter sweep 10 energy=-2.381489999595 maxlinkdim=49 time=0.172\n\nRun dmrg with free fermion starting state\nAfter sweep 1 energy=-2.381489929965 maxlinkdim=49 time=0.139\nAfter sweep 2 energy=-2.381489999588 maxlinkdim=49 time=0.165\nAfter sweep 3 energy=-2.381489999594 maxlinkdim=48 time=0.161\nAfter sweep 4 energy=-2.381489999594 maxlinkdim=48 time=0.169\n\n\n\nThis page was generated using Literate.jl.","title":"Examples"}]
